sec.p:
Gear faults may result in various vibration changes on the surface of the gearbox as well as the sound field distributions visualized by NAH images. The changes on acoustic images can be depicted by textural features, which can be quantitatively described by various SGLCM-based feature descriptors. SGLCM is based on the estimation of second-order joint conditional probability density functions P(i, j, d, θ) (Wu et al., 1992), where d denotes the inter-sample spacing and θ expresses the direction angle. The (x,y)th element of one two-dimensional gray image is expressed as f (x, y). Each P(i, j, d, θ) denotes the transition probability from gray level i to j as follows:
(3)p(i,j,δ,θ)=#{[(x,y),(x+dx,y+dy)]|(x,y)=i,f(x+dx,y+dy)=j}
where the inter-sample spacing d indicates that (x,y) and (x + dx,y + dy) are d-pixels apart, # denotes the number of the type pixel pair satisfying the conditions.

SVM can be generalized to compute nonlinear decision surfaces by using a kernel method and the optimal hyperplane decision function is obtained:
(7)f(x)=sgn{∑αiK(xi·x)+b}
where K(xi·x) is kernel function and is instead of (xi·x) in equation (6). Here, the multi-classification function of Libsvm (Chang and Lin, 2001) is employed, in which the kernel function radial basis function (RBF; K(x,y)=e2) is applied. It combines several binary classifiers to solve the multiclass SVM problems, and the one-against-one strategy is applied (Hsu and Lin, 2002). This strategy constructs k(k − 1)/2 classifiers, where each one is trained on data from two classes. For arbitrary two class data, ith and jth, one binary SVM classifier is produced. After all k(k − 1)/2 classifiers are constructed, the ‘Max Wins’ voting strategy is used as follows. If x is judged as in the ith class, the vote for the ith class is increased by one. Otherwise, the jth is increased by one. Here x is predicted in the class with the largest vote.
